name: LibreNMS
description:
LibreNMS is a community-based GPL-licensed network monitoring system (NMS). It is an autodiscovering PHP/MySQL/SNMP based network monitoring which includes support for a wide range of network hardware and operating systems including Cisco, Linux, FreeBSD, Juniper, Brocade, Foundry, HP and many more.

We intend LibreNMS to be a viable project and community that:

* encourages contribution,
* focuses on the needs of its users, and
* offers a welcoming, friendly environment for everyone.

The Debian Social Contract will be the basis of our priority system, and mutual respect is the basis of our behaviour towards others. For more about the culture we're trying to build, please read the Freenode philosophy, including guidelines for running an IRC channel and being a community catalyst.

documentation_roadmap_justification: https://github.com/hyperledger/fabric-rfcs/ Fabric is managed like many of the other Hyperledger projects via an RFC process. We also have a published web presence for the active RFCs. We review them periodically in the maintainer's call.
documentation_architecture_justification: We have documented the architecture here https://hyperledger-fabric.readthedocs.io/en/latest/architecture.html and much of the documentation is focused on explaining the workings of the platform.

documentation_achievements_justification: all badges are displayed in the README https://github.com/hyperledger/fabric/blob/main/README.md
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: https://github.com/hyperledger/fabric-docs-i18n maintains a number of crowd-sourced translations for the Fabric documentation.
internationalization_justification: We have translated the docs, but the software does not itself generate text intended for end users. A separate UI is typically developed as a function of the aaS or application using Fabric.
sites_password_security_justification: Fabric supports HSM for keys and a wallet for client certificates. https://hyperledger-fabric.readthedocs.io/en/latest/hsm.html
maintenance_or_update_justification: Fabric has an LTS release strategy documented here https://github.com/hyperledger/fabric#releases All prior releases are available via github.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: Hyperledger Fabric participates in the Hyperledger vulnerability reporting process described here https://wiki.hyperledger.org/display/SEC/Defect+Response. We also have a bug bounty program managed by hackerOne that ensures that credit is given where due.
vulnerability_response_process_justifica: Hyperledger Fabric participates in the Hyperledger vulnerability reporting process described here https://wiki.hyperledger.org/display/SEC/Defect+Response
coding_standards_enforced_justification: Fabric is written primarily in Go and uses all the OSS Golang linters in its CI/CD pipeline for every PR submitted
build_standard_variables_justification: The build does not override user settings.
installation_standard_variables_justific: Fabric builds Docker container images that are deployed independently of the Fabric project itself (eg Kubernetes, Rancher, Docker Swarm, etc)
installation_development_quick_justifica: Fabric includes a GH Actions-based CI/CD pipeline.
contributors_unassociated_justification: many of the top contributors work for different companies https://insights.lfx.linuxfoundation.org/projects/hyperledger%2Ffabric/dashboard
copyright_per_file_justification: there is a linting test that checks for this before a file is merged
license_per_file_justification: Fabric uses SPDX headers. There is a linter for this as well.

name: SPARK 2014
description: SPARK 2014 is the new version of SPARK, a software development technology specifically designed for engineering high-reliability applications. It consists of a programming language, a verification toolset and a design method which, taken together, ensure that ultra-low defect software can be deployed in application domains where high-reliability must be assured, for example where safety and security are key requirements.

contribution_justification: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
license_location_justification: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/blob/master/COPYING3
floss_license_justification: The GPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The GPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification:
The SPARK User's Guide is online at http://docs.adacore.com/spark2014-docs/html/ug/

Sources for it are in the project repository under https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/tree/master/docs/ug
documentation_interface_justification:
The SPARK Reference Manual describing the input SPARK programming language is online at http://docs.adacore.com/spark2014-docs/html/lrm/

Sources for it are in the project repository under https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/tree/master/docs/lrm

The output format(s) are described in the SPARK User's Guide at http://docs.adacore.com/spark2014-docs/html/ug/en/source/how_to_view_gnatprove_output.html
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: Interim versions are put on git, not just final versions.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification:
Professional releases use a versioning scheme MAJOR.MINOR, where MAJOR is the 2-figures year of the main release, and MINOR is 0 for beta version, 1 for main release, 2 for corrective release. For example: 18.2

Community releases use a versioning scheme YEAR, where year is the 4-figures year of the release. For example: 2018
version_semver_justification: We were originally using Semantic Versioning, but we have now adopted across AdaCore a simpler versioning scheme: a date-based scheme YYYY-MM-DD for intermediate daily releases, and year-based YY.num for official releases: YY.0 for beta release, YY.1 for main release, YY.2 for first corrective release, followed by further corrective releases YY.3, YY.4 etc. on branches where corrective releases are produced for multiple years.
version_tags_justification: All releases use git branches. Professional releases use the version number as branch name, for example 18.2, and community releases use gpl-YEAR as branch name, for example gpl-2018.
release_notes_justification:
High-level release notes are published in HTML for each major release since 2017:
http://docs.adacore.com/live/wave/spark2014-release-notes/html/spark2014_release_note/index.html

More detailed release notes are also published in textual format, simply update the final year in the URL for getting the release notes of that particular year:
http://docs.adacore.com/R/relnotes/features-spark-18
release_notes_vulns_justification: There are no publicly known vulnerabillities.
report_process_justification: Yes, either GitHub issue tracker or SPARK public mailing list https://lists.adacore.com/mailman/listinfo/spark2014-discuss
report_responses_justification: Yes, we usually fix quickly all bugs reported publicly.
enhancement_responses_justification: Yes, we usually answer quickly to all public enhancement requests, although we do not commit to implementing them all.
report_archive_justification:
Yes, via GitHub isue tracker: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/issues
and SPARK public mailing list archive: https://lists.adacore.com/pipermail/spark2014-discuss/
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Vulnerabilities should be reported like other issues using GitHub issue tracker: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/issues
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Private vulnerability reports are only supported through a support contract with AdaCore.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: No external reports so far, so this is vacuously true.
build_justification: The README at the root of the GitHub repository has a section on Building SPARK. It explains how to get the sources, points to the top-level Makefile and lists the dependencies.
build_common_tools_justification: Standard Unix Makefiles are used to build the project, as well as standard builders for every sub-project, depending on the programming language. For example we use GPRbuild for Ada code and OCamlbuild for OCaml code.
build_floss_tools_justification: Repo page https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014 explains how to build SPARK with a GNAT Community or FSF compiler, including the dependencies on other FLOSS software.
test_invocation_justification: Testsuite relies on publicly available AdaCore framework E3, available at https://github.com/AdaCore/e3-core
test_most_justification: Code coverage is measured every night over the complete testsuite (including the public testsuite) using GNATcoverage to measure code coverage. Most of the code is currently covered at statement level, and we aim at increasing coverage with time.
test_policy_justification: All changes go through review and require testing, both for new functionalities and bug fixes.
tests_are_added_justification: Tests are added as new functionality is added.
tests_documented_added_justification: Major new functionality is currently only provided by the entities mentioned in the governance section of the README at https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014. Tests are in fact part of any change, in particular for new functionality (small or large). This can be checked easily as tests and code are submitted in the same patches in the same repository, and must go through peer review.
warnings_justification: Code is compiled with warning flags -gnatwae (all GNAT warnings enabled and considered as errors) or -gnatg (all GNAT warnings enabled for work on the compiler and considered as errors). We also run nightly the CodePeer static analyzer on all Ada code and maintain a baseline of zero findings from static analysis.
warnings_fixed_justification: Warnings are considered as errors and stop the build, so must always be addressed.
warnings_strict_justification: Warnings are considered as errors and stop the build.
know_secure_design_justification: Project developers are formal verification experts who develop security-related checking tools.
know_common_errors_justification: Project developers are formal verification experts who develop security-related checking tools.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: No such vulnerabilities at this time.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: No such vulnerabilities at this time.
static_analysis_justification:
CodePeer static analysis tool (https://www.adacore.com/codepeer) is applied every day to the current Ada codebase for SPARK toolset, which includes both the gnat2why and gnatprove executables (and a few smaller executables produced in gnatprove project). We maintain a baseline of zero findings by static analysis, therefore any new finding must be addressed by developers in the following days in order to either fix the bug, or justify the finding.

No static analysis is performed today on the external dependencies Why3 and Alt-Ergo (in OCaml) or Z3 and CVC4 (in C++).
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: CodePeer targets common CWE, as documented in CodePeer User's Guide: http://docs.adacore.com/live/wave/codepeer/html/codepeer_ug/messages_and_annotations.html#support-for-cwe
static_analysis_fixed_justification: CodePeer messages are reviewed and addressed by developers in the following days in order to either fix the bug, or justify the finding.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Compilation in debug mode for testing is done with all Ada runtime checks, plus assertions (with -gnata) and validity checks (with -gnatVa and pragma Initialize_Scalars). This is stricter than most dynamic checking tools for other languages.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Ada and OCaml are the two main languages used. Both are memory safe languages.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Compilation in debug mode for testing is done with all Ada runtime checks, plus assertions (with -gnata) and validity checks (with -gnatVa and pragma Initialize_Scalars).
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: SPARK is a verification tool, hence does not expose the user to risks of attacks through vulnerabilities. Still, bugs are fixed quickly when discovered.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Continuous integration is provided by AdaCore infrastructure.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests. Discussions about SPARK occur on a public mailing list https://lists.adacore.com/mailman/listinfo/spark2014-discuss
no_leaked_credentials_justification: No valid private credentials are leaked.
english_justification: All documentation is in English, and the project accepts bug reports and comments in English.
hardening_justification: As a verification tool, SPARK is not concerned with security vulnerabilities in the tool itself.
hardened_site_justification: X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: On Linux/Mac, all artefacts are installed under the target installation directory. Uninstall can be done by deleting the directory. Install is facilitated for the Community release by providing an installer for Windows/Linux/Mac.
dco_justification: All contributors outside of AdaCore are required to sign a CLA: https://github.com/AdaCore/contributing-howto/blob/master/adacore-corporation-cla.md
governance_justification:
The SPARK project is a result of the collaboration of AdaCore, Altran and Inria. The collaboration with the three entities takes the form of a partnership between Altran and AdaCore, and a joint lab between AdaCore and Inria (https://www.adacore.com/proofinuse), with AdaCore in the lead role. 

The governance and key roles are documented in the project README at https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014
roles_responsibilities_justification: The README documents key roles and responsibilities: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014
access_continuity_justification: AdaCore as a commercial entity ensures the project will continue with minimal interruption should a person be incapacitated or killed, as SPARK is a key product of the company: https://www.adacore.com/sparkpro
bus_factor_justification: AdaCore as a commercial entity ensures the project will continue with minimal interruption should a person be incapacitated or killed, as SPARK is a key product of the company: https://www.adacore.com/sparkpro
documentation_roadmap_justification: The SPARK roadmap is presented every year at the AdaCore Tech Days, for example in 2019: https://events.adacore.com/techdaysparis2019/agenda (follow links to access slides)
documentation_architecture_justification: The tool architecture is described as part of the developer documentation at https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/blob/master/docs/develguide/tool_structure.rst
documentation_security_justification: As a verification tool, SPARK is not concerned with security vulnerabilities. The benefits of using SPARK for developing secure software are described in particular in a booklet (https://www.adacore.com/books/adacore-tech-for-cyber-security) and on the MITRE listing of CWE-compatible products (http://cwe.mitre.org/compatible/questionnaires/55.html)
documentation_quick_start_justification: The SPARK User's Guide contains a tutorial section at http://docs.adacore.com/spark2014-docs/html/ug/en/tutorial.html
documentation_current_justification: All documentation is maintained up-to-date daily with changes to the code, in particular the SPARK User's Guide at http://docs.adacore.com/spark2014-docs/html/ug/index.html
documentation_achievements_justification: The GitHub page uses the CII badge: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: All functionalities of GNATprove are available through the command-line tool gnatprove, except for some interactions features specific to working inside an IDE (for example, display of the trace corresponding to a counterexample).
internationalization_justification: There has not been requests for internationalization that could justify this effort so far. Part of the documentation has been translated into Japanese: https://www.adacore.com/resources-in-japanese
sites_password_security_justification: Project website uses GitHub which does not store additional passwords than the one for GitHub itself.
maintenance_or_update_justification: Previous versions of SPARK 2014, starting with the first one issued in 2014, can be downloaded at https://www.adacore.com/download/more. We pay extraordinary attention to maintain backwards compatibility between versions, and have not needed to issue migration guidelines so far.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: As a verification tool, SPARK is not concerned with security vulnerabilities in the tool itself.
vulnerability_response_process_justifica: The GitHub issue tracker is used for all issues: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/issues
coding_standards_justification: We use the standard warnings and style checks selected for GNAT development, triggered by compilation switches -gnatw.g (see http://docs.adacore.com/live/wave/gnat_ugn/html/gnat_ugn/gnat_ugn/building_executable_programs_with_gnat.html#warning-message-control) and -gnatyg (see http://docs.adacore.com/live/wave/gnat_ugn/html/gnat_ugn/gnat_ugn/building_executable_programs_with_gnat.html#style-checking)
coding_standards_enforced_justification: Warnings and style checks selected for GNAT development are enforced by the GNAT compiler.
build_standard_variables_justification: The Makefiles do use environment variables which can be overwritten.
build_preserve_debug_justification: GNATprove can be build in debug mode by passing the value Debug for the Build environment variable (also the default mode).
build_non_recursive_justification: Each binary can be built independently using the appropriate builder (GPRbuild for Ada code, OCamlbuild for OCaml code). The Makefiles only provide the scripting around calls to the builders.
build_repeatable_justification: Internal quality assurance at AdaCore relies on the reproducibility of builds.
installation_standard_variables_justific: The installer proposes a candidate location for installation that the user can override.
installation_development_quick_justifica: This is described in the README at https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014#6-building-spark
external_dependencies_justification: There are few dependencies that are listed in the README: https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014#6-building-spark
dependency_monitoring_justification: As a verification tool, SPARK is not concerned with security vulnerabilities in the tool itself.
updateable_reused_components_justificati: The components used by GNATprove should be separately built.
interfaces_current_justification: This is met to the best of our knowledge.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Internal quality assurance at AdaCore ensures that all commits are included in a Continuous Build and Test. Results are reported to the author.
regression_tests_added50_justification: A test is added for all bugs fixed.
test_statement_coverage80_justification: Coverage is over 95% on the public testsuite at https://github.com/AdaCore/spark2014/tree/master/testsuite/gnatprove. Coverage is measured every night using source code instrumentation with GNATcoverage. Files from the GNAT compiler used to build the AST are excluded from coverage analysis, as most of the code in these files is not used in the project.
test_policy_mandated_justification: This is part of quality assurance at AdaCore.
implement_secure_design_justification: As a verification tool, SPARK is not concerned with security vulnerabilities in the tool itself.
input_validation_justification: As a verification tool, SPARK is not concerned with security vulnerabilities in the tool itself.
signed_releases_justification: Currently, we only provide a hash of the installation package at https://www.adacore.com/download/more
assurance_case_justification: As a verification tool, SPARK is not concerned with security vulnerabilities in the tool itself.

name: Hyperledger Iroha
description: Iroha is a simple and straightforward DLT platform for asset and identity management. It has client libraries for mobile and web application development; novel consensus, called YAC, and SQL-powered validation.
description_good_justification: Use-cases and features are described here https://soramitsu.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/IS/pages/65241150/Pieces+of+work
interact_justification: We put contributing information in the readme and here: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>. The requirements are described in https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md and pull requests template
contribution_requirements_justification: A signed developer certificate of origin is required to contribute https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/LICENSE.
floss_license_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: Did not find license in the OSI list. The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: iroha.readthedocs.io
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: We typically use multiple branches and pull requests are reviewed by multiple people before being merged. The develop branch is used for interim releases that are not yet ready to be merged into master and released.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: The project uses https://wiki.hyperledger.org/community/release_taxonomy with semantic versioning
report_archive_justification:
All issues can be viewed at https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/issues.
Closed issues can be viewed by searching: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aclosed
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Vulnerabilities are posted to JIRA or https://www.hyperledger.org/blog/2018/04/17/hyperledger-bug-bounty-program-now-open Bug Bounty program
build_floss_tools_justification: The project code is build via cmake only. CMake is open source project — https://cmake.org
test_justification: Gtest and Gmock frameworks are used: https://github.com/google/googletest
test_most_justification: Coverage report: https://out-8410xxpdz.now.sh; Test report: https://file-npmqkpbcrk.now.sh; tests cover most of the branches where possible
test_policy_justification: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md there is a requirement for new change
tests_are_added_justification: We add unit tests using gtest and run these in Jenkins as part of the CI process: https://jenkins.soramitsu.co.jp/job/iroha/job/iroha-hyperledger/job/dev/
tests_documented_added_justification: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hyperledger/iroha/master/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md <!-- * All new code must have code coverage above 70% (https://docs.codecov.io/docs/about-code-coverage). -->
warnings_justification: We use clang-format linter with these rules: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/.clang-format
warnings_fixed_justification: Warning are addressed as JIRA tasks
warnings_strict_justification: No warnings are allowed in compiler's output for pull request build
know_secure_design_justification: Maintainer's team has a dedicated security role, and currently there is a team member assigned
delivery_mitm_justification: We use transaction hash storage in transactions in order to prevent replay attacks
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: https://www.cvedetails.com/cve/CVE-2018-3756/ all vulnerabilities are fixed in latest releases
static_analysis_fixed_justification: All vulnerabilities are reported in Hyperledger Jira and fixed timely
dynamic_analysis_justification: We use valgrind and sanitizers. We also use fuzzing for all client- and peer-facing components
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: We use fuzzing tool: libfuzz & protomutator for gRPC endpoints
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: All vulnerabilities are reported in Hyperledger Jira and fixed timely
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: https://jenkins.soramitsu.co.jp/job/iroha/job/iroha-hyperledger/ test results are attached to every build, which is triggered with each commit
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on pull requests. Our project has rocket.chat and mailing lists: https://chat.hyperledger.org/channel/iroha https://lists.hyperledger.org/g/iroha
english_justification: We use JIRA bugs: https://jira.hyperledger.org/secure/Dashboard.jspa. Documentation is available at https://iroha.readthedocs.io
crypto_used_network_justification: Right now we don't have implementation for this, but project roadmap already has items for TLS support in gRPC
hardened_site_justification: We use GitHub: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha
installation_common_justification: Software is installed as a docker container https://hub.docker.com/r/hyperledger/iroha/. Uninstallation process is typical.
build_reproducible_justification: We use docker environment to build the code and all the dependencies are included in docker-build image here: https://hub.docker.com/r/hyperledger/iroha/ so anyone can reproduce the build
dco_justification: The project requires contributors to check DCO. https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md "Signed-off every commit with DCO: Signed-off-by: $NAME <$EMAIL>. You can do it automatically using git commit -s."
access_continuity_justification: Hyperledger organization is a governing organization with multiple community architects: https://www.hyperledger.org/about/leadership. Also, project's bus factor is relatively high, which is good.
bus_factor_justification:
Analysis over "dev" branch on December 4 2018: (this tool was used — https://github.com/aserg-ufmg/Truck-Factor/tree/master/gittruckfactor)

2018-12-04 15:34:40 INFO  hyperledger/iroha: Extracting and calculating authorship information...

documentation_roadmap_justification:
https://soramitsucoltd.aha.io/published/e9bce93777c2c4b2448e4e6e78e90b4f?page=1

Information should be updated regularly at iroha.tech/roadmap
documentation_current_justification: The project always have the latest documentation. Releases have their own version of documentation. The project uses readthedocs service in order to fulfill the requirement
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: All functionality is available from a keyboard. All the output is available in stdout and should be processed with required software.
internationalization_justification: Project's docs are translated into any language with the help of community: https://poeditor.com/join/project/SFpZw7o33o
sites_password_security_justification: We don't provide any service or authentication of our users.
maintenance_or_update_justification: We support backwards compatibility by versioning of client API and business objects. If migration has to occur — we will post a description for upgrade.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio:
Credits are given in the release notes: 

https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/releases

"Fix of critical vulnerabilities discovered during the security audit

Previously, several problems existed:

Blocks can be signed more than once by the same peer (fixed in #1193)
Transactions can be signed more than once by the same signatory (fixed in #1302)
If ed25519 library was modified to use a non-deterministic nonce, these vulnerabilities were likely to be used. Thanks to @dhuseby who helped us to unveil this tricky part of ed25519."
coding_standards_enforced_justification: we use git hooks that check if the code is conformant to clang-format checks
build_standard_variables_justification: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CMakeLists.txt CMake and Iroha support clang, gcc and msvc compilers
build_preserve_debug_justification: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CMakeLists.txt debugging information is preserved in Debug build
build_non_recursive_justification: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CMakeLists.txt all the modules are clearly non-cross dependent
build_repeatable_justification: We use docker image for dependencies that provides guarantee for bit-for-bit result, `develop-build` https://hub.docker.com/r/hyperledger/iroha/
installation_standard_variables_justific: Software is usually installed manually with docker container
installation_development_quick_justifica: Software is usually installed manually with docker container. Tests can be run as explained here: https://iroha.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guides/build.html#running-tests-optional
external_dependencies_justification: All external dependencies are resolved via CMakeLists https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/CMakeLists.txt
dependency_monitoring_justification: CMake files are periodically checked to contain vulnerable dependencies
updateable_reused_components_justificati: All the dependencies are listed as cmake modules. Inside each cmake file a dependency is fixed to a specified commit. Thus anyone can modify the commit, identity and update the version of dependency. Example https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/master/cmake/Modules/Findgrpc.cmake
interfaces_current_justification: We don't use deprecated API where possible
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Check build history and commit pipeline here https://jenkins.soramitsu.co.jp/job/iroha/job/iroha-hyperledger/job/dev/
regression_tests_added50_justification: There is a policy that for each bug there should be a regression. Example of fix and regression: https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/pull/1894
test_statement_coverage80_justification: Coverage report does not meet this criteria https://out-8410xxpdz.now.sh
test_policy_mandated_justification: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hyperledger/iroha/master/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md <!-- * All new code must have code coverage above 70% (https://docs.codecov.io/docs/about-code-coverage). -->
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: We don't support other algorithms, but our crypto component is pluggable
crypto_credential_agility_justification: Files with private keys are separate from other information
signed_releases_justification: Until first major release we don't sign our releases
version_tags_signed_justification: Until first major release we don't sign our releases
contributors_unassociated_justification:
https://poeditor.com/projects/view?id=171155

We have unassociated contributors to our documentation, which has more than 20 pages in its printed version
copyright_per_file_justification:
In the vast majority of files there is a copyright header, including "Copyright Soramitsu Co., Ltd. All Rights Reserved."

Examples:
https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/81a1fd4986d466f08d0a4c6d70781f8dc528b908/irohad/ametsuchi/impl/postgres_block_query.cpp
https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/81a1fd4986d466f08d0a4c6d70781f8dc528b908/test/module/irohad/ametsuchi/postgres_query_executor_test.cpp
license_per_file_justification:
Files are regularly checked by Hyperledger and all source code is commented with SPDX-License-Identifier, example:
https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/81a1fd4986d466f08d0a4c6d70781f8dc528b908/irohad/ametsuchi/impl/postgres_block_query.cpp
https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/blob/81a1fd4986d466f08d0a4c6d70781f8dc528b908/test/module/irohad/ametsuchi/postgres_query_executor_test.cpp
small_tasks_justification: Although we have https://github.com/hyperledger/iroha/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3Agood-first-issue in GitHub, we are switching now to Hyperledger JIRA board, where contributors can pick any task from the backlog: https://jira.hyperledger.org/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=215&projectKey=IR&view=planning
require_2FA_justification: All Iroha maintainers have 2FA turned on in GitHub with OTP generated in Google Auth app
secure_2FA_justification: All Iroha maintainers have 2FA turned on in GitHub with OTP generated in Google Auth app
security_review_justification: Security review was prepared for The Linux Foundation authored by Nettitude in 12th April 2018

name: Genetic circuit design automation
contribution_justification: Non-trivial contribution file in repository: <https://github.com/CIDARLAB/cello/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md>.

name: matador
description: matador is a ORM framework written in C++. It aims to encapsulate all database stuff (database backends, sql statements, serialization of objects) and provides the user an easy to use interface and a unique container for all objects. Given this container the user has a centralized point of storage for all objects at hand but with the ability to create views on concrete object types.
